import Checklist from '../../../../components/Checklist.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Project 4: The integrated app" description="Integrate third-party APIs and catch when AI hallucinates their documentation.">
  <h1 class="mb-2">Project 4: The Integrated App</h1>
  <p class="text-xl text-primary font-medium mb-6">"I can integrate third-party services and catch when AI hallucinates their APIs."</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What you'll build</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Vinyl Vault — an online record store for a small shop in Fitzroy, Melbourne. Product catalog with search and filtering by artist or genre. Shopping cart. Stripe checkout for card payments. Google Maps embed showing the physical store location. Order confirmation emails. React frontend, FastAPI backend, PostgreSQL, Docker.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What's new (the +1)</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Third-party API integration. Stripe handles payments, Google Maps shows the store. The skill isn't making the API call — AI does that. The skill is verifying AI's integration against the real documentation. AI hallucinates API methods, parameters, and response formats. You need to catch it.</p>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Why this matters:</strong> When AI writes Stripe integration code, it generates something that <em>looks</em> correct — real-sounding endpoint names, plausible parameters, familiar response shapes. But it might use a deprecated method, invent a parameter that doesn't exist, or expect a response field that Stripe never returns. The only way to catch this is to open the official documentation and verify, line by line. This is the #1 new skill in Project 4.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What success looks like</h2>
  <Checklist items={[
    "A working online store with real Stripe test payments that complete successfully",
    "A Google Maps embed that loads and shows the correct store location",
    "Zero hallucinated API calls in the codebase — every external integration verified against official docs",
    "A PRD, design spec, architecture, and backlog you created yourself (same process as P3)",
    "Confidence in the verification process: you know how to check any API integration",
  ]} />

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What you'll learn</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-8">
    <li>Integrate Stripe payments (test mode) — checkout flow, payment confirmation</li>
    <li>Embed Google Maps with the correct location</li>
    <li>Verify AI output against official API documentation</li>
    <li>Detect hallucinated methods, parameters, and response formats</li>
    <li>Handle webhook events (Stripe payment confirmation)</li>
    <li>Work with API keys and secrets securely (environment variables, never committed to git)</li>
    <li>Write an OpenAPI spec before implementation</li>
    <li>Run end-to-end tests with Playwright</li>
    <li>Track errors with Sentry</li>
    <li>Create architecture diagrams with Excalidraw</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Prerequisites</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-8">
    <li>Completed <a href="/web-dev/projects/3">Project 3</a> and <a href="/web-dev/checkpoints/after-p3">Checkpoint After Project 3</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Estimated time</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">1-2 weeks. The planning process follows P3's pattern. The new time investment is in API verification — checking every external integration against the real docs.</p>

  <div class="mt-8 p-6 bg-primary-bg rounded-lg border border-primary/20 text-center">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">Start with the requirements</h2>
    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Meet the client, understand the brief, then write the PRD.</p>
    <a
      href="/web-dev/projects/4/requirements"
      class="inline-block bg-primary hover:bg-primary-dark text-white font-semibold py-3 px-6 rounded-md transition-colors min-h-[44px]"
    >
      Start with the requirements →
    </a>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
